        p.regs.spsr_el1 = STUB_SPSR_EL0;
        p.ttbr0_pa = ttbr0_pa;
        p.asid = asid;
        p.next_ready = None;
        // Clear the boot RTS_NO_PRIV: VM now has an address space and can run.
        p.rts_flags.store(0, Ordering::Relaxed);

        let _ = writeln!(
            Pl011::new(),
            "[as] vm nr={} ttbr0_pa={:#x} asid={} entry={:#x}",
            p.nr.get(),
            p.ttbr0_pa,
            p.asid,
            entry,
        );
    }

    // The page-table tree is durable via `ttbr0_pa`; don't run `destroy`.
    core::mem::forget(aspace);

    // SAFETY: single-threaded boot; no other PROC_TABLE / RUNQ borrow is live.
    unsafe { sched::enqueue(VM_PROC_NR) };
}
```

**Key observations:**
- Allocates fresh `AddrSpace` (page-table tree via frame allocator)
- Loads ELF via `crate::boot_image::elf::load_into()` returning entry point
- Allocates and maps one zeroed RW stack frame at `VM_STACK_VA = 0x0020_0000`
- Allocates 8-bit ASID via `alloc_asid()`
- Writes `(ttbr0_pa, asid, entry, sp)` to proc slot
- **Clears `RTS_NO_PRIV` flag** by storing `0` to `rts_flags` (line 264) — marks proc runnable
- Enqueues on scheduler via `sched::enqueue(VM_PROC_NR)`
- Forgets `aspace` (tree ownership stays via `ttbr0_pa`)

