## 6. VFS server (`servers/vfs/`) — skeletal

### `servers/vfs/src/main.rs`

Structurally identical to DS's main but with **no registry** and an init callback that **publishes to DS via SENDREC**:

```rust
#![cfg_attr(not(test), no_std)]
#![cfg_attr(not(test), no_main)]
// _start shim + panic handler identical to vm/ds.

fn vfs_init(endpoint: Endpoint, name: &[u8; SYS_GETINFO_NAME_LEN]) -> i32 {
    // Publish "vfs" -> endpoint to DS. SENDREC blocks the sender until DS is in
    // its receive loop and replies; safe at boot (see ordering note).
    sef_publish_to_ds(endpoint, name)   // shared helper, see item 7
}

fn main() -> ! {
    let sef = sef_startup(SefConfig { init_fresh: Some(vfs_init), signal_handler: None })
        .unwrap_or_else(|_| loop { core::hint::spin_loop() });
    let mut msg = Message { m_source: 0, m_type: 0, payload: [0u8; 96] };
    loop {
        if sef.receive(&mut msg) != 0 { continue; }
        match msg.m_type {
            // No file ops yet. Unknown request: reply EINVAL so a caller's
            // SENDREC doesn't hang. (A bare SEND with no reply expected would
            // also be fine to drop, but EINVAL is safe and explicit.)
            _ => { let src = msg.m_source; msg.m_type = EINVAL; msg.m_source = 0;
                   let _ = ipc_send(src, &mut msg); }
        }
    }
}
```

### Boot-ordering safety of the VFS→DS SENDREC at init (confirmed)

- **Why it doesn't deadlock:** `vfs_init` runs inside `sef_startup`, i.e. during VFS's *first* scheduled run. A SENDREC from VFS to DS just blocks VFS until DS executes `ipc_send` back to it. DS's `ds_init` seeds its own table **without IPC** and returns, so DS reaches its `loop { sef.receive(...) }` and will pick up VFS's DS_PUBLISH, reply OK, and unblock VFS. DS never SENDRECs back to VFS during DS's own init, so there is no cycle.
- **Load/enqueue order does not matter for correctness**, only for promptness: SENDREC blocks regardless of which server runs first. If VFS runs before DS, VFS blocks SEND-side until DS's RECEIVE; if DS runs first it blocks in RECEIVE(ANY) until VFS sends. Either interleaving converges. (For tidiness, the pack/load order vm→ds→vfs means DS is enqueued before VFS, so the common path is DS-waiting-first.)
- **Priv wiring is already in place** (item from established facts): `init_boot_image` fills every SRV_T priv's `ipc_to` over `[0, n_active=16)`, so VFS(1)↔DS(5)↔VM(7)↔SYSTEM all hold the needed `ipc_to` bits and `k_call_mask` covers `SYS_GETINFO` for the `GET_WHOAMI` handshake. **No new priv install code.**

