## 7. Shared init helper — put it in `server-rt` (recommended, DRY)

Add `sef_publish_to_ds` to server-rt. Rationale: server-rt already depends on `minix-ipc` and `kernel-shared`, is `#![forbid(unsafe_code)]` (the helper is pure message-building + an `ipc_sendrec`, no unsafe), and the spec says "every server publishes its endpoint at init." Centralizing avoids three copies of the same payload-marshaling + SENDREC.

New file `server-rt/src/ds.rs` (or fold into `init.rs`):

```rust
// SPDX header
use minixrs_ipc::ipc_sendrec;
use minixrs_kernel_shared::Message;
use minixrs_kernel_shared::callnr::{DS_PUBLISH, SYS_GETINFO_NAME_LEN};
use minixrs_kernel_shared::com::{DS_PROC_NR, boot_endpoint};
use minixrs_kernel_shared::endpoint::Endpoint;
use minixrs_kernel_shared::error::OK;

/// Publish `endpoint` under `name` (16-byte NUL-padded key) to DS via a SENDREC.
/// Returns OK on success, the trap error, or DS's negative reply m_type.
/// Used from a server's SEF `init_fresh` callback (slice 4.2).
pub fn sef_publish_to_ds(endpoint: Endpoint, name: &[u8; SYS_GETINFO_NAME_LEN]) -> i32 {
    let mut msg = Message { m_source: 0, m_type: DS_PUBLISH, payload: [0u8; 96] };
    msg.payload[0..16].copy_from_slice(name);
    msg.payload[16..20].copy_from_slice(&endpoint.to_ne_bytes());
    let rc = ipc_sendrec(boot_endpoint(DS_PROC_NR), &mut msg);
    if rc != OK { return rc; }
    msg.m_type   // DS reply: OK or negative error
}
```

Export it from `server-rt/src/lib.rs` (`pub use ds::sef_publish_to_ds;`). VFS uses it directly in `vfs_init`. **VM also gains an init callback now** ("every server publishes its endpoint at init"): change vm/main.rs's `sef_startup` call from `init_fresh: None` to `init_fresh: Some(vm_init)` where `vm_init` is just `sef_publish_to_ds`. DS is the exception — it must **not** use this helper (would SENDREC to itself = deadlock); DS seeds directly in `ds_init`.

**Coverage note:** `sef_publish_to_ds` contains an `ipc_sendrec` (SVC trap), so like `sef.rs` it can't run under host `cargo test`. Put it in its own module and add it to `sonar.coverage.exclusions` (see item 8). It has no pure logic worth host-testing (just marshaling), so no host tests; the message format is exercised indirectly by DS's registry tests + the QEMU `[ipc]` trace.

