### `servers/ds/src/registry.rs` — pure, host-tested (modeled on `vm/region.rs`)

```rust
// SPDX header (BSD-3-Clause, 2025-2026 ...)
use core::cell::UnsafeCell;
use minixrs_kernel_shared::callnr::SYS_GETINFO_NAME_LEN;     // 16
use minixrs_kernel_shared::error::{EINVAL, ENOMEM};

const KEY_LEN: usize = SYS_GETINFO_NAME_LEN; // 16
const CAP: usize = 16;                         // covers all boot servers + slack

#[derive(Copy, Clone)]
struct Entry { key: [u8; KEY_LEN], endpoint: i32, in_use: bool }
impl Entry { const EMPTY: Self = Self { key: [0; KEY_LEN], endpoint: 0, in_use: false }; }

#[repr(transparent)]
struct Registry(UnsafeCell<[Entry; CAP]>);
// SAFETY: DS is a single EL0 thread, no interrupt handlers of its own; touched
// only from DS's straight-line receive loop. (Same invariant as vm/region.rs.)
unsafe impl Sync for Registry {}
static TABLE: Registry = Registry(UnsafeCell::new([Entry::EMPTY; CAP]));

// ---- pure logic on a borrowed slice, the host-testable core ----
fn publish_in(t: &mut [Entry; CAP], key: &[u8; KEY_LEN], ep: i32) -> i32 { /* OK / EINVAL / ENOMEM */ }
fn retrieve_in(t: &[Entry; CAP], key: &[u8; KEY_LEN]) -> Option<i32> { ... }
fn check_in(t: &[Entry; CAP], key: &[u8; KEY_LEN]) -> bool { ... }

// ---- thin public wrappers over the static (excluded paths are only these) ----
pub fn publish(key: &[u8; KEY_LEN], ep: i32) -> i32 { /* unsafe { &mut *TABLE.0.get() } -> publish_in */ }
pub fn retrieve(key: &[u8; KEY_LEN]) -> Option<i32> { ... }
pub fn check(key: &[u8; KEY_LEN]) -> bool { ... }

#[cfg(test)] mod tests { /* host tests on *_in helpers + EMPTY array */ }
```

Semantics: `publish_in` rejects an all-zero/empty key (`EINVAL`); updates an existing entry with the same key (re-publish overwrites endpoint, idempotent — important for DS seeding itself then nothing republishing); else claims first free slot, `ENOMEM` if full. `retrieve_in`/`check_in` scan for `in_use && key == k`.

**Host tests** (mirror region.rs's coverage discipline):
- publish then retrieve returns the endpoint; check returns true.
- retrieve/check of an absent key → None / false.
- empty key → EINVAL; full table → ENOMEM; re-publish same key updates endpoint (one slot, not two).
- distinct keys coexist.

### `servers/ds/src/main.rs` — SEF loop (modeled on vm/main.rs)

```rust
#![cfg_attr(not(test), no_std)]
#![cfg_attr(not(test), no_main)]
mod registry;

use minixrs_ipc::ipc_send;
use minixrs_kernel_shared::Message;
use minixrs_kernel_shared::callnr::{DS_PUBLISH, DS_RETRIEVE, DS_CHECK, SYS_GETINFO_NAME_LEN};
use minixrs_kernel_shared::error::{OK, ESRCH, EINVAL};
use minixrs_server_rt::{SefConfig, sef_startup};

#[cfg(not(test))]
#[unsafe(no_mangle)]
#[cfg_attr(target_os = "none", unsafe(link_section = ".text._start"))]
pub extern "C" fn _start() -> ! { main() }

#[cfg_attr(test, allow(dead_code))]
fn main() -> ! {
    let _sef = sef_startup(SefConfig {
        init_fresh: Some(ds_init),     // seeds DS's own entry directly (no IPC)
        signal_handler: None,
    }).unwrap_or_else(|_| loop { core::hint::spin_loop() });

    let mut msg = Message { m_source: 0, m_type: 0, payload: [0u8; 96] };
    loop {
        if _sef.receive(&mut msg) != 0 { continue; }
        match msg.m_type {
            DS_PUBLISH  => handle_publish(&mut msg),
            DS_RETRIEVE => handle_retrieve(&mut msg),
            DS_CHECK    => handle_check(&mut msg),
            _ => { msg.m_type = EINVAL; msg.m_source = 0; let _ = ipc_send(reply_to, &mut msg); }
        }
    }
}
```

**DS self-publish without IPC deadlock (the key correctness point):** in `ds_init(endpoint, name) -> i32`, DS calls `registry::publish(name, endpoint)` **directly** — no SENDREC. `sef_startup` already learned DS's own endpoint+name via `GET_WHOAMI` and hands them to the init callback. Seeding the static table in-process means DS never needs to SENDREC to itself (which would deadlock: a SENDREC to self has no second party). Return `OK`. (Use the 16-byte `name` as the key; it is already NUL-padded by `GET_WHOAMI`.)

Handlers read the key from `payload[0..16]` into a `[u8;16]`, dispatch to `registry`, and reply via `ipc_send(msg.m_source, &mut msg)` after setting `m_type`/payload and zeroing `m_source` (the kernel overwrites source on delivery — same idiom as vm/main.rs's `handle_brk`). Note `m_source` is captured *before* mutation. Payload accessors (`rd`/`wr` for i32) copied from vm/main.rs's `wr_i32`/native-endian helpers.

Reply contracts:
- publish → `m_type = registry::publish(&key, ep)` (OK / EINVAL / ENOMEM).
- retrieve → `match registry::retrieve(&key) { Some(ep) => { wr_i32(payload,16,ep); OK } None => ESRCH }`.
- check → `wr_i32(payload, 16, registry::check(&key) as i32); m_type = OK`.

